emale; Krao, a seven-year-old hairy Laotian girl who was marketed as Darwin's "missing link"; the "Last of the Mysterious Aztecs" and African "Cannibal Kings," who were often merely Irishmen in blackface. Upending our tendency to read late twentieth-century conceptions of disability onto the bodies of freak show performers, Durbach shows that these spectacles helped to articulate the cultural meanings invested in otherness--and thus clarified what it meant to be British—at a key moment in the making of modern and imperial ideologies and identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAbnormalities, HumanzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aFreak showszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a1847.  aanthropology.  abritish culture.  acannibal kings.  aconjoined twins.  acultural otherness.  acultural studies.  adeformity.  adisability.  aelephant man.  aeuropean history.  aexploitation.  afreak show performers.  afreak shows.  agreat britain.  ahuman bodies.  aimperial ideology.  alalloo.  amissing link.  amodern history.  amodern identity.  amodern sensibilities.  anational identity.  anonfiction.  apsychology.  ascientists.  asocial history.  asocial issues.  asocial purpose.  asocial purposes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025768940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094489340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944893/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alle